'''Mohamed El Sayed Mohamed El Shenawy Gomaa''' ({{langx|ar|محمد السيد محمد الشناوي جمعة}}; born 18 December 1988) is an Egyptian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for [[Egyptian Premier League]] club [[Al Ahly FC|Al Ahly]], which he [[Captain (association football)|captains]], and the [[Egypt national football team|Egypt national team]].

El Shenawy began his career as a youth player with Al Ahly but was released in 2009, joining [[Tala'ea El Gaish SC|Tala'ea El Gaish]]. He spent time on loan with [[Haras El Hodoud SC|Haras El-Hodoud]] before joining [[Petrojet SC|Petrojet]] in 2013. He returned to Al Ahly in July 2016 and then displaced [[Sherif Ekramy]]; he is considered one of the best goalkeepers in Africa. He helped the club win four consecutive [[Egyptian Premier League]] titles ([[2016–17 Egyptian Premier League|2016–17]], [[2017–18 Egyptian Premier League|2017–18]], [[2018–19 Egyptian Premier League|2018–19]] and [[2019–20 Egyptian Premier League|2019–20]]) and two consecutive [[CAF Champions League]] titles ([[2019–20 CAF Champions League|2019–20]] and [[2020–21 CAF Champions League|2020–21]]).

El Shenawy made his international debut for Egypt in March 2018 in a [[Exhibition game#Association football|friendly]] match. He was selected as the starting goalkeeper for their squad at the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]], playing in their opening two matches.

==Club career==
El-Shenawy began his career in the youth system at his hometown club El-Hamoul SC before moving to [[Al Ahly FC|Al Ahly]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContentP/6/232893/Sports/Ahly-sign-Petrojet-goalkeeper-Mohamed-ElShennawy.aspx |title=Ahly sign Petrojet goalkeeper Mohamed El-Shennawy |publisher=Ahram Online |date=10 July 2016 |accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref> joining the club at the age of fourteen in 2002.<ref name="rest">{{cite web |url=https://www.egypttoday.com/Article/8/46523/No-rest-for-Shennawy |title=No rest for Shennawy |publisher=Egypt Today |date=29 March 2018 |accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref> He failed to make a league appearance for the senior squad before being released by the club in 2009.<ref name="kf1">{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2016/07/10/official-ahly-sign-el-shennawy/ |title=Al Ahly sign Mohamed El-Shennawy |website=KingFut.com |date=10 July 2016 |accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref> Following his release, he joined fellow [[Egyptian Premier League]] side [[Tala'ea El Gaish SC|Tala'ea El Gaish]].<ref name="rest"/> During his time with El Gaish, El Shenawy spent time on loan with [[Haras El-Hodood SC|Haras El-Hodood]].

Mohamed El-Shenawy joined [[Petrojet SC|Petrojet]] in 2013. His form during the 2015–16 season, keeping a joint league-high eleven clean sheets in twenty-two appearances, including a run of seven matches without conceding, led his former club Al Ahly to attempt to resign him after attracting the attention of manager [[Martin Jol]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2016/03/16/al-ahly-eye-petrojet-goalkeeper/ |title=Al Ahly open negotiations for Petrojet goalkeeper |website=KingFut.com |author=Marwan Ahmed |date=16 March 2016 |accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref>

El-Shenawy rejoined Al-Ahly in July 2016,<ref name="kf1"/> establishing himself in the first team over [[Sherif Ekramy]] after keeping five clean sheets in seven matches during January 2018, including helping the side to a 1–0 victory over [[Al-Masry SC|Al-Masry]] in the [[2017 Egyptian Super Cup]]. He also recorded the highest percentage of clean sheets by any goalkeeper in the Egyptian Premier League.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2018/02/03/winners-losers-january-egyptian-league/2/ |title=January 2018: Egyptian Premier League Winners and Losers |website=KingFut.com |author=Sina Isaac |date=3 February 2018 |accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref> In his first four seasons, El-Shenawy helped the club win the Egyptian Premier League in consecutive seasons.<ref name="Soccerway">{{Soccerway|87623|accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref> He also won the [[2019–20 CAF Champions League]] to participate in the [[2020 FIFA Club World Cup]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/clubworldcup/news/perseverance-pays-off-for-el-shenawy |title=Perseverance pays off for El Shenawy |website=FIFA |date=10 February 2021 }}</ref> in which he managed in the 3rd place playoff, to save two penalties in the 3–2 penalty shootout win over [[Sociedade Esportiva Palmeiras|Palmeiras]], as the game ended 0–0 after 90 minutes and extra time.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/clubworldcup/news/el-shenaway-spot-kick-saves-seize-ahly-bronze#al-ahly-sc-v-se-palmeiras-fifa-club-world-cup-qatar-2020-x4462 |title=El Shenaway spot-kick saves seize Ahly bronze |website=FIFA |date=11 February 2021 }}</ref> In the [[2025 FIFA Club World Cup Group A#Al Ahly vs Inter Miami CF|first match]] of [[2025 FIFA Club World Cup]] against [[Inter Miami CF|Inter Miami]], El-Shenawy produced a number of saves, including a long shot from [[Lionel Messi]] in the final minutes of the game, as the match ended in a goalless draw.<ref>{{cite news|title=Messi, Inter Miami tie Al Ahly 0-0 in Club World Cup opener in front of 60,927 fans|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/sports/mls/inter-miami/article308579235.html|publisher=Miami Herald|date=14 June 2025|access-date=15 June 2025}}</ref>

==International career==
For the national team, Mohamed El-Shenawy represented Egypt at the under-18 level and later played for the [[Egypt national under-20 football team]] in the [[2007 African Youth Championship]]. From 2013, he received several call-ups to the [[Egypt national football team|senior Egypt]] side before making his international debut in a 2–1 [[Exhibition game|friendly]] defeat against [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2018/03/24/ronaldo-beat-salah/ |title=Ronaldo's late double cancels Salah opener as Egypt lose to Portugal |website=KingFut.com |author=Khaled Ali |date=24 March 2018 |accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref> He earned praise for his performance in the match, with national team goalkeeping coach Ahmed Nagy commenting "He had a great game; I am so happy with his performance He deserves to be with the national team."<ref name="rest"/>

In May 2018, he was named in Egypt’s preliminary squad for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] in Russia.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/world-cup/egypt-world-cup-squad-profile-2018-fixtures-group-team-news-schedule-dates-times-odds-tv-channel-a8381771.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220515/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/world-cup/egypt-world-cup-squad-profile-2018-fixtures-group-team-news-schedule-dates-times-odds-tv-channel-a8381771.html |archive-date=15 May 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |title=Egypt World Cup squad guide |newspaper=The Independent |last=Watson |first=Jack |date=4 June 2018 |accessdate=3 November 2018}}</ref> He played in warm up friendly matches against [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]] and [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]] prior to the tournament and was chosen as the starting goalkeeper for their opening match of the tournament against [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]], winning only his fourth cap, ahead of [[Essam El-Hadary]] and club teammate Ekramy.<ref name="nft">{{NFT player|id=70799|accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref> He was named Man of the Match in the first match after making several saves during a 1–0 defeat however, he declined to accept the award in the players' tunnel after the match due to its sponsorship by [[Budweiser]] and was only photographed with the award.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Beiler |first1=Des |title=Egypt goalkeeper declines Budweiser-sponsored 'Man of the Match' trophy at World Cup |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/early-lead/wp/2018/06/18/egypt-goalkeeper-declines-budweiser-sponsored-man-of-the-match-trophy-at-world-cup/?noredirect=on |website=The Washington Post |accessdate=19 June 2018}}</ref>
As a Muslim, El-Shenawy is forbidden from drinking alcohol.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/my/features/egypt-goalkeeper-mohamed-el-shenawy-turns-down-sponsored-man-match-trophy |title=Egypt goalkeeper Mohamed El-Shenawy turns down sponsored man-of-the-match trophy |publisher=FourFourTwo |date=19 June 2018 |accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref> Teammate Ekramy and Egyptian team director Ihab Leheta later attempted to persuade him to accept the award as a "historic" prize, but he again refused.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.egyptindependent.com/egypts-goalkeeper-refuses-to-take-over-man-of-the-match-prize/ |title=Egypt's goalkeeper refuses 'Man of the match' prize |publisher=Egypt Independent |date=17 June 2018 |accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref>

He retained his place for Egypt's second group match as they were eliminated after suffering a 3–1 defeat to hosts [[Russia national football team|Russia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44439062 |title=Russia 3–1 Egypt |publisher=BBC Sport |author=Michael Emons |date=19 June 2018 |accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref> He was included in Egypt's squad for the [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/africa/59818147 |title=Afcon 2021: Aston Villa's Trezeguet returns to join Salah and Elneny in Egypt squad |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=29 December 2021 |accessdate=29 December 2021 |archive-date=31 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211231083437/https://www.bbc.com/sport/africa/59818147 |url-status=live }}</ref> where the team reached the [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations final|final]] but lost to [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]] in a penalty shootout.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12532825/senegal-0-0-egypt-senegal-win-4-2-on-penalties-sadio-mane-puts-penalty-miss-behind-him-to-score-winning-spot-kick-in-shootout |title=Senegal 0-0 Egypt (Senegal win 4-2 on penalties): Sadio Mane puts penalty miss behind him to score winning spot kick in shootout |publisher=Sky Sports |date=7 February 2022 }}</ref>

On 2 December 2025, El Shenawy was called up to the Egypt squad for the [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cafonline.com/afcon2025/news/egypt-name-final-28-man-squad-for-totalenergies-caf-afcon-2025-salah-leads-pharaohs-charge/|title=Egypt name final 28-man squad for TotalEnergies CAF AFCON 2025, Salah leads Pharaohs' charge|publisher=[[Confederation of African Football]]|date=2 December 2025|access-date=12 December 2025}}</ref>

